{
  "explanation": "The defendant was found guilty of embezzling $25,000, which represents a serious breach of fiduciary duty and trust toward their employer. However, as a judge, I must weigh both mitigating and aggravating factors. The mitigating factors in this case are substantial: the defendant has no prior criminal record, committed the offense to resolve pressing personal debts rather than for extravagant personal enrichment, and has already begun making restitution by partially paying back the stolen funds. The outburst from the spectator demanding a 10-year sentence is entirely inappropriate and has been completely disregarded, as judicial sentences must be rooted in law, proportionality, and guidelines, not emotional public outbursts. For a first-time, non-violent white-collar offense of this magnitude, a lengthy prison term is counterproductive to the goal of the defendant continuing to earn an income to pay full restitution. A brief period of incarceration is sufficient to serve as punishment and a deterrent. Therefore, I sentence the defendant to 12 months of incarceration, after which they will be required to serve probation and complete the financial restitution.",
  "verdict": 12
}
